32 17–604.1.
33 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “ALL APPLICABLE APPRENTICESHIP TRAINING
34 PROGRAMS” MEANS EACH APPRENTICESHIP TRAINING PROGRAM THAT HAS A
35 GEOGRAPHIC AREA OF OPERATION THAT INCLUDES THE LOCATION OF THE

10 HOUSE BILL 864
1 COVERED PROJECT AND HAS A USUAL AND CUSTOMARY BUSINESS PRACTICE OF
2 ENTERING INTO AGREEMENTS WITH EMPLOYERS FOR THE PLACEMENT OF
3 APPRENTICES IN THE COVERED CRAFT.
4 (B) THE SECRETARY MAY WAIVE THE REQUIREMENTS UNDER § 17–603 OR
5 § 17–604 OF THIS SUBTITLE IF A CONTRACTOR OR SUBCONTRACTOR SUBMITS A
6 WRITTEN WAIVER APPLICATION, INCLUDING ANY SUPPORTING DOCUMENTATION
7 REQUIRED BY THE SECRETARY, DEMONSTRATING THAT THE CONTRACTOR OR
8 SUBCONTRACTOR:
9 (1) SUBJECT TO SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION, HAS REQUESTED
10 QUALIFIED APPRENTICES FROM ALL APPLICABLE APPRENTICESHIP TRAINING
11 PROGRAMS; AND
12 (2) FOR EACH REQUEST:
13 (I) THE REQUEST HAS BEEN DENIED FOR A REASON THAT IS
14 NOT THE RESULT OF A REFUSAL BY THE CONTRACTOR OR SUBCONTRACTOR TO
15 COMPLY WITH THE ESTABLISHED STANDARDS AND REQUIREMENTS OF THE
16 APPRENTICESHIP TRAINING PROGRAM; OR
17 (II) THE APPRENTICESHIP TRAINING PROGRAM HAS FAILED TO
18 RESPOND TO THE REQUEST WITHIN 10 BUSINESS DAYS AFTER THE DATE ON WHICH
19 THE APPRENTICESHIP TRAINING PROGRAM RECEIVED THE REQUEST.
20 (C) TO REQUEST QUALIFIED APPRENTICES FROM AN APPRENTICESHIP
21 TRAINING PROGRAM, A CONTRACTOR OR SUBCONTRACTOR SHALL SUBMIT:
22 (1) A REQUEST BY TELEPHONE AND IN WRITING SENT
23 ELECTRONICALLY AND BY REGISTERED MAIL; AND
24 (2) A REQUEST TO AN APPRENTICESHIP TRAINING PROGRAM WITH
25 WHICH THE CONTRACTOR OR SUBCONTRACTOR DOES NOT HAVE AN EXISTING
26 PARTICIPATION AGREEMENT, AT LEAST 90 CALENDAR DAYS BEFORE THE DATE THE
27 CONTRACTOR OR SUBCONTRACTOR EXPECTS TO USE APPRENTICE LABOR.
28 17–605.1.
29 (A) WHILE CONSTRUCTION ACTIVITY ON A COVERED PROJECT IS ONGOING,
30 EACH CONTRACTOR AND SUBCONTRACTOR PERFORMING WORK ON THE COVERED
31 PROJECT SHALL SUBMIT A MONTHLY REPORT TO THE DEPARTMENT THAT
32 INCLUDES:

HOUSE BILL 864 11
1 (1) FOR EACH APPRENTICE OR JOURNEYWORKER:
2 (I) THE NAME OF THE APPRENTICE OR JOURNEYWORKER;
3 (II) THE NAME OF THE ASSOCIATED APPRENTICESHIP TRAINING
4 PROGRAM; AND
5 (III) THE APPRENTICE REGISTRATION OR IDENTIFICATION
6 NUMBER;
7 (2) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF APPRENTICES AND LABOR HOURS
8 WORKED, CATEGORIZED BY TRADE OR CRAFT; AND
9 (3) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF JOURNEYWORKERS AND LABOR HOURS
10 WORKED, CATEGORIZED BY TRADE OR CRAFT.
11 (B) WITHIN 60 DAYS AFTER COMPLETING WORK ON A COVERED PROJECT,
12 EACH CONTRACTOR AND SUBCONTRACTOR SHALL SUBMIT TO THE DEPARTMENT:
13 (1) A STATEMENT OF THE TOTAL NUMBER OF LABOR HOURS OF WORK
14 ON A COVERED PROJECT, INCLUDING CONSTRUCTION, ALTERATION, AND REPAIR
15 WORK, PERFORMED BY AN APPRENTICE OR JOURNEYWORKER; AND
16 (2) IF APPLICABLE, A WRITTEN DECLARATION AND SUPPORTING
17 DOCUMENTS JUSTIFYING ANY WAIVER RECEIVED UNDER § 17–604.1 OF THIS
18 SUBTITLE.
19 (C) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL MAINTAIN ON ITS WEBSITE:
20 (1) DATA AGGREGATED FROM THE REPORTS RECEIVED UNDER
21 SUBSECTIONS (A) AND (B) OF THIS SECTION SHOWING THE USE OF QUALIFIED
22 APPRENTICES AND JOURNEYWORKERS ON COVERED PROJECTS; AND
23 (2) DESCRIPTIONS OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES OF ANY WAIVER
24 GRANTED UNDER § 17–604.1 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
25 17–606.
26 (a) A contractor or subcontractor that fails to meet the requirements of this
27 subtitle shall be liable for an amount equal to:
28 (1) twice the amount of unpaid apprenticeship training contributions
29 required by §§ 17–603 AND 17–604 OF this subtitle; AND

12 HOUSE BILL 864
1 (2) $100 MULTIPLIED BY THE TOTAL LABOR HOURS FOR WHICH THE
2 REQUIREMENT UNDER § 17–603 OF THIS SUBTITLE WAS APPLICABLE.
3 (b) (1) In this subsection, “willfully” means representations or omissions
4 known to be false or made with deliberate ignorance or reckless disregard for their truth or
5 falsity.
6 (2) Any person, firm, or corporation that is found to have made willfully a
7 false or fraudulent representation or omission regarding a material fact in connection with
8 prevailing wage records required by this section shall be liable for a civil penalty in an
9 amount of up to $1,000 for each employee and each falsified record.
10 (3) Penalties shall be recoverable [in civil actions and paid to the State]
11 UNDER THE MARYLAND FALSE CLAIMS ACT.
12 (c) (1) The Secretary shall adopt regulations to establish administrative
13 procedures for the collection of payments under this subtitle.
14 (2) (i) The Secretary may file suit to enforce this section in any court of
15 competent jurisdiction.
16 (ii) In an action filed under this subsection, the court shall require
17 the contractor or subcontractor to pay the amount required by subsection (a) of this section,
18 including interest, reasonable counsel fees, and court costs.
19 17–607.
20 THE SECRETARY SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS NECESSARY TO CARRY OUT THE
21 REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SUBTITLE.
22 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
23 October 1, 2026.

